mdElement.text:
Create the swim lanes from the pallet and then drag and drop the blocks for the system of interest, external users and systems on to the corresponding swim lane.

The type of the inputs and outputs (e.g., pins) should match the type of flows that are on the connectors in the ibd.

Add or display ports by selecting button in context specific pallet (e.g. smart manipulator).

Add flows as shown in another version of this ibd that includes flows.
Specify the external interfaces for System XYZ

The requirements are organized in a containment tree that corresponds to the organization of the specification.

The requirements can also be displayed in tabular format. You can add text and relationships in the requirements in the table if desired. The table can be exported in html and csv (i.e., Excel).
Add flows by dragging and dropping the blocks or signals from the input/output definition package in the browser. The type of the flows are defined on the input-output definitions.
Specify the external interfaces for System XYZ

The Analysis1 block refers to the subject of the analysis (i.e., soa), which in this case refers to the Context block. The Analysis1 block is also composed of the constraint block used to specify the parameters and equations.

The equations and parameters can be added to the constraint block. In order to define units, the parameters are typed by value types.
If desired, a parametric diagram can be created for the Analysis block. In the parametric diagram, the parameters of the analysis can be bond to the properties of the design.
Double click use case to navigate to Activity Diagram
You can directly use blocks to represent the actors
The properties of the blocks are bound to the parameters of the equations.

<html> <head> <style> p {padding:0px; margin:0px;} </style> </head>
<body> Define a block for each engineering analysis to be performed such as performance analysis, reliability analysis, and cost analysis. </body>
</html>
For each analysis, define another block definition diagram to specify the subject of the analysis and the constraints to be used.
Modify diagram properties by right clicking on the white space in the diagram, and then select diagram properties.
Select Model Navigation Guide to Navigate the Model
If MD crashes and you are unable to reboot MD, you can select the backup file (.bak) from the same folder as your other MD file.

This is a model template to help you get started modeling. You can modify, add or delete the model elements from this template. Select Save Project As from the file menu and save with your project name. This template does not include all SysML diagrams, but they can be added..
Generate HTML version of the model by selecting Web Publisher 2 Wizard from the Options Menu
This is being replaced by a window on startup to select memory with a recommended memory level.
This should be replaced by a simple tutorial with a selected set of features.
Navigate different levels of the model starting at the Context Level, then System, Subsystem, and Component Levels. Use this as a template to define your model.
Define the system context as an aggregation of the system of interest and its external users, external systems and the natural environment (not included)

Define the System XYZ external interfaces with the external users and systems by defining and connecting the system ports to the external users and systems. This is done by selecting the System XYZ Context and creating its internal block diagram .
Include a separate package for external interfaces that get exported.
Typing of ports? If you choose to add more detailed definition of the ports, you must type the ports with interface blocks or blocks that are defined on a separate bdd.
Define items that flow as blocks or signals. These can be used to type the item flows on the internal block diagrams and the pins on the activity diagram.
